 gaps that they claim are "not relevant".  Verant is usually reluctant to comment on discipline issues, but they have posted something on the EQ web site.  I suggest everyone take a look at that before forming an opinion.<P><P>------------------<BR>Heilig Hangranate<BR>46 cleric<BR>Quellious</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">kitsinu</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">My guess is that they had the primary tank in a position where they were falling out of melee range and only getting hit once per round or something similar.  Verant has a statement concerning this on their forum page that states that the primary target was in range only 25% of the time due to the "z-axis".  As hard as these mobs hit, most falling damage would be trivial by comparison.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#f7f7f7"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Falconquick</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Update: Then, Brad McQuaid said:<P>On June 4th, 2001, SOE banned and/or suspended 28 players belonging to the guild Conquest. Plainly put, they were cheating, we observed them cheating, they knew they were cheating, they admitted they were cheating, and they got caught.<P>While SOE does not want to spoil the game by releasing full details of the cheats to all players, basically the 28 Conquest players were (among other things) purposely using world geometry, aspects of the hate list, the "z" coordinate and its nullification of NPC's ability to summon, and multiple atmospheres (e.g. water/land) to arrange dragon-type encounters so they could attack without getting hit back for the vast majority of the time that it took to kill the monster. In short, what they did was carefully orchestrate 100,000+ hps encounters so that, for 75% or more of the time that it took to kill the encounter, the monster got beaten on and was not able to fight back.<P>In addition, SOE staff observed various members of the guild discussing the cheating -- these comments include:<P>"we're useing [sic] massive amounts of exploits and u send a gm down here?"<P>"Any lead GM shows up, this show is over."<P>"yeah, this is the most impressive Itz-guyversploit [sic] to date"<P>"every guild exploits these"<P>The EverQuest Rules of Conduct state, among other things: <P>"You will not exploit any bug in EverQuest and you will not communicate the existence of any such exploitable bug (bugs that grant the user unnatural or unintended benefits in game), either directly or through public posting, to any other user of EverQuest. You will promptly report any such bug via the in-game /bug command or via the eqtesting@verant.com email address."<P>"Disciplinary issues involving guilds will also be addressed on a broader basis. Guilds whose members habitually violate any of the Rules of Conduct . . . may be disbanded."<P>As a result of this unfortunate incident, (i) most of the participants were suspended for one week, (ii) a few, who had received previous warnings or suspensions, were banned, and (iii) this guild has been disbanded.<P>SOE regrets having to take these measures, but SOE is committed to protecting the health and viability of the game and of the EverQuest community. We'd also like to correct a few related misconceptions regarding this event: (i) Conquest did not complete the encounter - SOE staff inadvertently spawned the Sleeper during its efforts to stop the cheating, (ii) the "human figures" in some screenshots are a result of the screenshot taker not patching, and (iii) the zone is complete and working -- once SOE has patched fixes to these exploits we encourage players to wake the Sleeper.<P>We appreciate everyone's emails with regards to questions and we do hope this will assist everyone in an understanding of the situation.<P>-The EverQuest Customer Service Team<P>--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>Hmmm. I wonder what happend to:<P>It is our policy not to discuss disciplinary actions taken on players with other players. These actions are considered confidential and we only will communicate directly to those players involved in the incident.<P>I am sorry that we will not be able to answer question on this issue. Please communicate to other members of the guild that unless they were directly involved in the incident they will receive this same response.<P>Michelle Butler<BR>EverQuest Customer Service Manager<BR>Sony Online Entertainment<P>--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<P>Oh. This from the Lum forums:<P>Severian: Your point in general is valid: we've always been clear as to what our policy is regarding commenting on bannings/suspensions and the like. Going forward, however, we are changing this policy: we will continue to respect customer (and former customer) privacy to the extent that we'll not talk about specific individual's, their names, character names, private communications between them and us, etc. <P>If, however, an event like this one (multiple bannings/suspensions) comes under the public eye, we will (at our descretion) post a general statement regarding this issue such that it's at the very least 'our word against their's' as opposed to 'their word against silence'. <P>-Brad<BR>Check more of the story at <A HREF="http://www.mobhunter.com" TARGET=_blank>www.mobhunter.com</A> </FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#dedfdf"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Aaldiana D'Ozz</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">PS...VI is full of it.  Mobs summon on the Z-axis just fine.  They summon out of water just fine.  They continue to even melee on the Z-axis just fine.<P>The ONLY thing that might be considered an exploit that I've gathered from this whole thing (though I'm sure there is still some info not being stated) is using a rez as a way to save/heal someone from battle as well as using rez effects to avoid the slow effect of th